<font color="#FF0000">SW'S FADING AWAY</font><br>
<tt>Mon Oct 13 19:35:32 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
<br><br>
SW said  &quot;We in our isolated world will not tell our stories to our children because we want to spare them the pain.&quot;  I spoke with a child of a vet on-line.  They could see the effects the war had on their father but could not know how or why without a willingness on his part to speak. They wanted the stories as a legacy for no more Vietnams.   The things left unsaid frequently make them appear to be worse than they are in reality and generally, the repeated stories do not have the personal destructive power as having lived it.   For a child who wants you to speak, refusal to do so may cause just as much pain as the stories.  <br><br>
Who is the &quot;they&quot; you refer to when you say &quot;they ask for reconciliation, or a common ground.  The sacrifice must be theirs.  We have made ours.&quot;    And.. what sacrifices can they make to bring about reconciliation?<br>

<p><code>--   (Class Lass) </code><p>


